00:16:50.800 --> 00:16:53.829
purpose of this thing, this is a C

00:16:53.839 --> 00:16:56.790
vectorization backend for our custom RL

00:16:56.800 --> 00:16:58.870
environments. So the idea is you run a

00:16:58.880 --> 00:17:01.030
bunch of threads. Maybe each uh each

00:17:01.040 --> 00:17:03.189
thread is going to like handle

00:17:03.199 --> 00:17:05.510
processing of environments kind of just

00:17:05.520 --> 00:17:07.990
as they're available. Um, but it's all

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:09.990
done in like shared memory with no

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:12.710
redundant copies. And the really key

00:17:12.720 --> 00:17:14.390
thing that I'm doing now, so I have a

00:17:14.400 --> 00:17:16.789
version of this in Python that's very

00:17:16.799 --> 00:17:20.309
very low overhead uh for Python. This

00:17:20.319 --> 00:17:22.230
will be a little bit faster. But then

00:17:22.240 --> 00:17:25.110
the key key thing about this is that I'm

00:17:25.120 --> 00:17:27.990
going to buffer the CUDA transfers. So

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.630
the idea is by the time that you need a

00:17:30.640 --> 00:17:32.950
new set of observations, not only is it

00:17:32.960 --> 00:17:34.310
already going to be computed, but it's

00:17:34.320 --> 00:17:36.070
already going to be moved onto the GPU

00:17:36.080 --> 00:17:37.990
for you. And that's the thing that makes

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:39.830
it substantially more complicated to do

00:17:39.840 --> 00:17:43.029
this correctly. Um, but this is going to

00:17:43.039 --> 00:17:44.789
eliminate like one of the biggest

00:17:44.799 --> 00:17:48.150
sources of overhead in RL in general,

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:50.549
I'd say. And it's one of the key things

